#Text=Tegucigalpa
#Text=Tegucigalpa
#Text=is the capital of and largest city in Honduras .
#Text=Understand

#Text=Tegucigalpa ( Hondurans in general , and people familiar with the city , shorten it to " Tegus " , while most locals actually use the full name ... ) is a great example Central America of urban sprawl gone amok , spread out across very hilly terrain .
#Text=Of course , the city , a 400 year-old mining center , has a depth that is there for those with time and nerve to find it .
#Text=It has a plethora of interesting , if decaying , old colonial buildings , and many old stone streets winding intriguingly up steep hills to hidden parks , stone steps , and old houses .
#Text=The defining event in recent Honduran history , and that of Tegucigalpa also , is Hurricane Mitch , which devastated the country in 1998 .
#Text=Mitch reportedly set the country back 50 years .
#Text=Tegus is still recovering from the massive flooding of the river , and equally massive landslides , both triggered by the rampant deforestation of the hills surrounding the city .
#Text=Indeed , signs of whole colonias ( neighbourhoods ) having slid off steep hills are still evident .
#Text=Workers continue to toil daily in the river , removing silt deposited by the flooding .
#Text=Many or most people lost friends and relatives during the crisis .
#Text=By bus
#Text=There are a number of bus international bus lines running to Tegus from other Central American capitals .
#Text=These offer first class , very comfortable service at a reasonable price .
#Text=A trip from Managua , San Salvador , or Guatemala City would cost between US$ 20 - 40 .
#Text=Ticabus
#Text=, is the most affordable and frequented by backpackers .
#Text=Hedman Alas , Nicabus , and King Quality , are other first class , reliable bus companies .
#Text=Of course , it is also possible to travel on less comfortable , less expensive lines , but this is difficult or impossible to plan from afar .

#Text=Internal travel in Honduras is easy enough , and made more easy thanks to the excellent transportation guide published by the Honduran tourism magazine called Honduras Tips , and available online at their website .
#Text=Travel from La Ceiba , on the north coast , Empresa de Bus Cristina provides good service , at around US$ 10 for the 7-8h trip .
#Text=95 % of buses coming to Tegus arrive into Comayagüela , the sister city of Tegucigalpa .
#Text=It is also reputedly one of the more dangerous parts of the city .
#Text=If arriving to Comayagüela after dark , do not walk around looking for a place to stay .
#Text=Even in the day , walking from bus stations in Comayagüela to a hotel or hostel any distance away would be a bit risky .
#Text=By plane
#Text=Toncontín International Airport
#Text=( TGU ) .
#Text=TGU is n't necessarily the best port of entry to the country though there are a bunch of flights to various US cities and throughout Central America .
#Text=San Pedro Sula is the other big airport and may sometimes be better value .
#Text=Unfortunately the airlines in Central America are still able to keep prices high and competition has n't yet gained much of a foothold , so flights inside the region can be pretty expensive .
#Text=Get around
#Text=The football ( soccer ) stadium is a great central point for learning your bearings map-wise of the city .
#Text=Several of the larger roads meet in a round-about that uses the stadium as its hub .
#Text=By taxi
#Text=As of June 2009 , taxis ( directos ) will cost ~L80 for a 20 minute cross-town trip .
#Text=Negotiating for the price ( before getting in ) is expected .
#Text=Taxi drivers are a bit wild , so buckle up ( oops , they do n't have seatbelts ) .
#Text=Prices increase with number of passengers and late at night .
#Text=Do n't be afraid to walk away from an expensive offer - taxis are everywhere and you 'll likely win the negotiation by walking away .
#Text=Colectivos
#Text=, like the city buses , run set routes from one point to another .
#Text=If you see a long line of people weaving down a side walk , this is most likely a collectivo line .
#Text=As of June 2009 , colectivos cost L11/person .
#Text=By bus
#Text=As of March 2007 , buses were L3 ( US$ 0.16 ) but run set routes that most visitors wo n't know .
#Text=There are common bus stops throughout the town , but are unlabeled .
#Text=Find a large group of people standing on the sidewalks for the largest selection of bus routes .
#Text=To know the main destinations of the buses , look on the front of the bus above the windshield .
#Text=Most buses operate to distinct neighborhoods and link to El Centro or the market in Comayaguela .
#Text=In the market in Comayaguela you can also find many inter-city buses with various prices and various levels of comfort , ranging from the most common chicken-bus to double decker luxury buses .
#Text=See
#Text=Parque La Leona
#Text=, is an old neighbourhood in the center of Tegus , overlooking the central park .
#Text=It is a bit of a labyrinth to make your way up the old steep windy streets to arrive at parque La Leona , but it is a nice park , with a beautiful view , and a relaxed atmosphere .

#Text=If walking , if you start facing the front door of the basilica in the central park , head to your left , and just keep walking up hill , and you will almost certainly hit the park as long as you continue upwards .
#Text=Or ask someone in the area .
#Text=In the park there is a little store/restaurant that sells typical Honduran food and has a patio overhanging from the park , with a spectacular view of the city , the valley , and the hills .
#Text=Parque el Picacho
#Text=, is a park overlooking the city which takes its name from the huge statue of Jesus Christ , also called " Cristo el Picacho " , which is visible from almost any point in the city .
#Text=Free parking is available at the entrance of the park , and entrance to the park is a nominal fee ( around 5 USD ) .
#Text=The views from the park are gorgeous .
#Text=The park is well maintained , clean , and seemingly not very busy ( though likely busier on weekends ) .
#Text=To get to the park if you do n't have a car , you can take the rapidito bus that passes the park on the way to El Hatillo .
#Text=The bus leaves from a few blocks north of the central park .

#Text=If you walk to the end of the Calle Peotanal that begins in front of the basilica , and follow it to the end , through the black gates , past the Museo de Identidad Nacional , all the way to the Bonillo Theatre , take a left there on the far side of the theatre , walk up one block and the bus leaves on the right .
#Text=Or just ask someone in this area .
#Text=On the rapidito ask the fare-taker to tell you when to get off for Picacho ( about a 5-10 minute walk in to the park gate , then a further 15 to the big Jesus ) .
#Text=The bus ride takes around 15 to 20 minutes .
#Text=National Zoo
#Text=, on the same hill as the Picacho statue , with tropical animals such as monkeys , bright-colored parrots , and others .
#Text=There is a separate entrance fee to enter the zoo .

#Text=While not a horrible zoo , and worth seeing if you do n't mind dropping a few dollars on the entrance fee , the zoo features mostly lethargic animals , the larger ones often noticeably insane as a result of their encagement .
#Text=The zoo has a variety of monkeys , crocodiles , a jaguar , tapirs ( anteaters ) , snakes , a collection of various raptors , and others .
#Text=Museo para la Identidad Nacional
#Text=( National Identity Museum ) , Calle El Telegrafo .
#Text=Museum of Honduran history and art .
#Text=Gets good reviews on other sites .
#Text=Museo Arqueologico
#Text=( Archaeology Museum ) .
#Text=Centro de tegucigalpa
#Text=Tegucigalpa is the capital city of Honduras .
#Text=Set in a central valley surrounded by mountains , it ’s known for its well-preserved Spanish colonial architecture .
#Text=The main Plaza Morazán is dominated by the 18th-century Cathedral of St. Michael the Archangel , with its baroque interior .
#Text=The Museum of National Identity traces the country ’s history .
#Text=It includes a virtual tour of the Copán Mayan ruins of western Honduras .

#Text=Movies
#Text=The Mall-Multiplaza has a Cinemark theater on the third floor .
#Text=Showtimes for popular movies frequently are half English with Spanish subtitles , and half dubbed in Spanish .
#Text=As of 2009 , tickets are L63/person .
#Text=Karaoke
#Text=.
#Text=There 's a karaoke bar a few blocks west of Parque Central .
#Text=There 's no song list , so you just need to think of songs and hope they have them .
#Text=They seem to have a good number of the more popular English karaoke songs ( aka Beatles ) , otherwise you can sing Spanish songs .
#Text=They also have cheap beer and they serve you small snacks ( crackers with tuna on them ) at no extra charge while you 're sitting down .
#Text=Parque de la Paz
#Text=, Just south of the Estadio Nacionál .
#Text=From the top you can see great panoramic views of Tegucigalpa , and the Peace Monument itself is also worth the trip up to see .
#Text=However , see below for VERY important safety instructions .
#Text=St. Michael 's Cathedral , Los Dolores Church , and San Francisco Church
#Text=.
#Text=These are all old Catholic churches well worth visiting , and La Merced and the Basilica de Suyapa are really good , too .

#Text=While not up to the level of a place like Cartagena , Colombia , such older churches are a nice surprise to the tourist who is n't aware that Tegucigalpa has older , Colonial-era attractions as well .
